HW4 Problem 1

(a)

  • Recall: from CLT we know that the limit distribution of standarized sample mean \[Z _ { n } = \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } }\] converges in distribution to \[Z \sim N ( 0,1 ).\]

  • Note 1: Since we are working with a relatively large number of subjects (\(n = 200\)), it is reasonable to use Central Limit Theorem and build \(95\)% confidence interval for the mean \(\mu\) parameter based on the limit normal distribution.

    • We do not have to assume normality of blood pressure in glaucoma patients then.

    • However, to invoke CLT, we need to assume independence of observations.

  • Note 2: We do not know the \(\sigma\) parameter true value. If the population standard deviation is unknown (which is often the case), then we use \(s\), standard deviation of the sample, as the estimate of \(\sigma\). Recall from Lecture 8: Slutskys theorem allows us to replace the unknown true population standard deviation \(\sigma\) with estimator of standard deviation \(s\)

Slutskys theorem: review

Slutskys theorem: application in our case

  • From CLT, \(Z _ { n }\) converges in distribution to \(Z \sim N ( 0,1 )\): \[ Z _ { n } = \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } \underset{d}{\to} N(0,1) \]

  • \(s\) sample estimator of standard deviation is a consistent estimator of true population standard deviation \(\sigma\), that is, converges in probability to \(\sigma\) (\(\sigma\) is a constant):

\[ s \underset{p}{\to} \sigma\;\;\; \text{ or equivalently: }\;\;\; \frac{\sigma}{s} \underset{p}{\to} 1 \]

  • We hence can invoke Slutskys theorem (second bullt point from the slide above) to say that:

\[ \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { s / \sqrt { n } } = \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } \cdot \frac{\sigma}{s}\underset{d}{\to} N(0,1) \cdot 1 \equiv N(0,1) \]

Solution

  • Using above (that is, approximation of \(\frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { s / \sqrt { n } }\) to standard normal distribution) we can write

\[ \begin{split} 0.95 & \approx P\left(z_{0.025} \leq \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { s / \sqrt { n } } \leq z_{0.975} \right) \\ & = P\left(z_{0.025} \leq \frac{140 - \mu}{25/\sqrt{200}} \leq z_{0.975} \right) \\ & = P\left( -140 + z_{0.025}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \leq -\mu \leq -140 + z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}}\right) \\ & = P\left(140 - z_{0.025}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \geq \mu \geq 140 - z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \right) \\ & = P\left( 140 - z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \leq \mu \leq 140 - z_{0.025}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \right) \\ & = P\left(140 - z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \leq \mu \leq 140 + z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \right) \end{split} \]

where the move from 2. to the end to the last line follows from the property of a quantiles of symmetric \(0\)-centered distributions: \(z_q = - z_{1-q}\).

  • Therefore, \(95\)% CI is of the form \[ \left(140 - z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}}, \; 140 + z_{0.975}\frac{25}{\sqrt{200}} \right) = (136.54, 143.46) \]

(b)

  • We want to test if the average systolic blood pressure (SBP) for persons with glaucoma is statistically different from the average SBP among persons without glaucoma (which is known to be \(130\)).

  • To test this, we perform a two-sided hypothesis test. Note: A one-sided hypothesis test would be an acceptable homework answer. The two sided test is more conservative and typically chosen in a real-world setting (where we should not know the direction o the difference a priori).

We define \(\mu_g\) as the mean SBP among persons with glaucoma and examine the null and alternative hypotheses: \[ \begin{aligned} H_0: & \mu_g = 130 \text{ (meaning there is no difference)} \\ H_a: & \mu_g \neq 130 \text{ (meaning there is a difference)} \end{aligned} \]

  • That is, we want to calculate the probability of observing a value as or more extreme than the observed one under the null hypothesis.

  • Distance between our observation (\(\bar{X}=140\)) and what is assumed under the null (\(\mu_g = 130\)) can be expressed as distance between the two: \(|\bar{X} - \mu_g| = |140 - 130| = 10\).

  • Observing a value as or more extreme than the observed one under the null hypothesis means observing distance as large, or larger: \(|\bar{X} - \mu_g| \geq 10\).

  • Probability of observing a value as or more extreme than the observed one under the null hypothesis means hence \(P(|\bar{X} - \mu_g| \geq 10)\).

  • Under the null hypothesis \(\mu_g = 130\), hence, given \(n=200\) is considered large enough, \[ \frac{\bar{X}_n - \mu_g}{s/\sqrt{n}} \overset{CLT + Slutsky}{\approx} N(0,1)\]

  • Denote \(Z \sim N(0,1)\). We can write

\[\begin{align*} P\left(\left|\bar{X} - \mu_g \right| \geq 10 \right)& = P\left(\left|\frac{\bar{X} - \mu_g}{25/\sqrt{200}}\right| \geq \frac{10}{25/\sqrt{200}} \right) \\ & \overset{CLT + Slutsky}{\approx} \; P(|Z| \geq 5.66) \\ & = P(Z \leq -5.66) + P(Z \geq 5.66) \end{align*}\]

pnorm(-5.66) + (1 - pnorm(5.66))
## [1] 1.51373e-08

HW4 Problem 2

  • Consider points (random variables) \(A\), \(B\) and an interval (random variable) \([A,B]\). \([A,B]\) is a two-sided 95% confidence interval for fixed, unknown parameter \(\mu\) if

\[ P\left( A \leq \mu \leq B \right) = 0.95. \]

  • Consider a point (random variables) \(A\) and an interval (random variable) \([A,\infty)\). \([A,\infty)\) is a one-sided 95% confidence interval for fixed, unknown parameter \(\mu\) if

\[ P\left( A \leq \mu \right) = 0.95. \]

Denote \(Z \sim N(0,1)\). Using above notation, consider \(A = \bar{X}-z_{.95} \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}\). We have

\[ \begin{split} P\left(A \leq \mu \right) & = P\left(\bar{X} - z_{.95} \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} \leq \mu \right) \\ & = P\left(\bar{X} - \mu \leq z_{.95} \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} \right) \\ & = P\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{s / \sqrt{n}} \leq z_{.95} \right) \\ & \approx_{CLT} P\left(Z \leq z_{.95} \right) \\ & = 0.95 \end{split} \]

HW4 Problem 3

(a)

  • Recall from the Lecture 9 page 21: \[\frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { S / \sqrt { n } }\] follows Students \(t\) distribution with \(n-1\) degrees of freedom (no approximation here, this is the exact distributional result).

  • Why not invoke Slutsky and use approx. normal distribution as we did in Problem 1 (where we invoked CLT + Slutsky)? Note that:

    • We know that when underlying distribution follows Normal distribution, \(\frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } \sim N(0,1)\) for any \(n\); hence in particular we could write that \(\frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } }\) converges in distribution to \(N(0,1)\), that is, \(\frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } \underset{d}{\to} N(0,1)\) (e.g.if we need this fact to invoke Slutskys theorem)

    • We know that \(\frac{S}{\sigma} \underset{p}{\to} 1\)

    • Hence we can use Slutsky and write a limit distribution as we did in Problem 1:

    \[\frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { s / \sqrt { n } } = \frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } \cdot \frac{s}{\sigma} \underset{d}{\to} N(0,1) \cdot 1 \equiv N(0,1)\] but be mindful this is a limit distribution and for \(n\) as small as \(n=25\) it is not plausible to assume the limit distribution holds (in our case, we are concerned as \(\frac{s}{\sigma}\) may be not close to \(1\) yet! Thus, we might be mis-estimating the true \(\sigma\)); hence we use more conservative \(t\)-distribution to describe distribution of \(\frac { \overline { X }_n - \mu } { s / \sqrt { n } }\) and provide \(90\)% confidence interval for \(\mu\):

\[ \begin{aligned} 0.90 & = P\left(t_{24,0.05} \leq \frac{7 - \mu}{3/\sqrt{25}} \leq t_{24,0.95} \right) \\ & = P\left( -7 + t_{24,0.05}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \leq -\mu \leq -7 + t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}}\right) \\ & = P\left(7 - t_{24,0.05}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \geq \mu \geq 7 - t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \right) \\ & = P\left(7 - t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \leq \mu \leq 7 - t_{24,0.05}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \right) \\ & = P\left(7 - t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \leq \mu \leq 7 + t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \right) \end{aligned} \] where the move from 2. to the end to the last line follows from the property of a quantiles of symmetric \(0\)-centered distributions: \(t_{\text{df};q} = - t_{\text{df};1-q}\).

  • Hence CI is of the form

\[ \left(7 - t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} , 7 + t_{24,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{25}} \right) \]

tstat <- qt(0.95, df = 24) * 3 / sqrt(25)
(CI <- 7 + c(-1,1) * tstat)
## [1] 5.973471 8.026529
(diff(CI)) # CI width
## [1] 2.053058

  • A 90% confidence interval for mean concentration of ampicillin among subjects on this particular dosage is \(\left(5.97, 8.03 \right)\).

  • Why we need to consider \(t\)-distribution instead of invoking CLT + Slutskys as in Problem 1? (Hint: consider sample size in this problem!)

(b)

  • The current confidence interval length is \(2.05\). To have it equal \(0.5\), from the \(CI\) formulation in last line of (a) we see that it narrows down to solving

\[ \begin{aligned} 2 \cdot t_{n-1,0.95} \cdot \frac{3}{\sqrt{n}} & \overset{set}{=} 0.5 \\ t_{n-1,0.95} \cdot \frac{3}{\sqrt{n}} & = 0.25 \end{aligned} \]

for some new \(n\).

  • But solving that is not simple as \(t_{n-1,0.95}\) involves \(n\) as well. We can, however, assume approximation of the \(t\)-student distribution for some updated (surely larger) \(n\) with the normal distribution; that is, solve with \(z_{0.95}\) instead of \(t_{n-1,0.95}\) to start with, and see if obtained \(n\) works for \(t\)-distribution same well. \[ \begin{aligned} z_{0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{n}} & \overset{set}{=} 0.25\\ \sqrt{n} & = 12 \cdot z_{0.95} \\ \sqrt{n} & = 19.73824 \\ n & = 389.5981 \approx 390 \end{aligned} \]
n <- 390
Zstat <- qnorm(0.95) * 3/sqrt(n)
CI <- 7 + c(-1,1)*Zstat 
(diff(CI))
## [1] 0.4997424

so indeed we see it is just less than \(0.5\) - great!

  • We use \(n = 390\) and check if this \(n\) yields desired CI width when we use \(t\)-distribution. We again use CI formula as derived in (a), \(\left(7 - t_{n-1,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{n}} , 7 + t_{n-1,0.95}\frac{3}{\sqrt{n}} \right)\). We have
n <- 390
tstat <- qt(0.95, df = n-1) * 3 / sqrt(n)
CI <- 7 + c(-1,1) * tstat
(diff(CI))
## [1] 0.5009354

we see it is not less than \(0.5\). Lets try with a sample larger by 1, then 2, then 3 elements.

n <- 391
tstat <- qt(0.95, df = n-1) * 3 / sqrt(n)
CI <- 7 + c(-1,1) * tstat
(diff(CI))
## [1] 0.5002913
n <- 392
tstat <- qt(0.95, df = n-1) * 3 / sqrt(n)
CI <- 7 + c(-1,1) * tstat 
(diff(CI))
## [1] 0.4996497

it is just less than \(0.5\) - great! Hence the answer is if we use the \(t\)-distribution, we require a sample size of \(392\).

Alternative solution

n <- 25
while (TRUE){
  tstat <- qt(0.95, df = n-1) * 3 / sqrt(n)
  CI <- 7 + c(-1,1) * tstat 
  CI.length <- diff(CI)
  if(CI.length < 0.5){
    break
  } else {
   n <- n + 1 
  }
}
print(n)
## [1] 392
